Global Coffee Domestic Consumption Analysis¶

Introduction¶

Coffee is a beverage brewed from roasted coffee beans. Darkly colored, bitter, and slightly acidic, coffee has a stimulating effect on humans, primarily due to its caffeine content. It has the highest sales in the world market for hot drinks. Wikipedia

We have been provided with a dataset containing coffee consumption for in the last 30 years for 55 countries.

Project Description¶

Goal/Purpose:

The goal is to analyze domestic coffee consumption in select countries over a 30 year period.

 

Questions to be Answered:

  • What countries have the highest domestic coffee consumption?
  • What countries have the lowest domestic coffee consumption?
  • What continents have the highest domestic coffee consumption on average?
  • What continents have the lowest domestic coffee consumption on average?
  • What coffee type is most consumed globally?
  • What coffee type is predominant in the top 10 countries with highest and lowest consumptions?
  • What is the trend of global average consumption?
  • What is the trend for each coffee type over the years?
  • What is the trend in the top 10 countries with highest and lowest consumption?

 

Data Description¶

Content:

This dataset is a CSV file of 55 data points which contains 33 columns.

 

Description of Attributes:

Column Description
Country The country where the coffee is being consumed
Coffee type The type of coffee being consumed
1990/91 to 2019/20 30 columns containing the coffee consumption data for each fiscal year from 2019/20 to 2019/20.
Total_domestic_consumption This is the total domestic consumption of the coffee type in the country over the entire period covered by the data.

 

Acknowledgements:

This dataset is provided by Brite Data.

Data Analysis¶

Total domestic consumption analysis¶

Country & Continent¶

Observations¶
  • In the 10 countries with lowest coffee consumption, Arabica is the predoninant coffee type with 50% of countries consuming Arabica exclusively.
  • 20 % of the bottom 10 consume both coffees while 30% consume Robusta exclusively. the remaining consume Arabica exclusively
  • None of the top 10 countries consume Robusta exclusively
Observations¶
  • In the top 10 countries with highest coffee consumption, Arabica is the predoninant coffee type.
  • 70 % of the top 10 consume both coffees while the remaining consume Arabica exclusively
  • None of the top 10 countries consume Robusta exclusively

Time series analysis¶

Global average consumption trends¶

yearly_average
1990/91 2.208590e+07
1991/92 2.289973e+07
1992/93 2.371862e+07
1993/94 2.388442e+07
1994/95 2.418132e+07
Observations¶

The decomposition of the global coffee consumption time series into its trend, seasonal, and residual components reveals the following:

Trend: There's a clear upward trend, indicating an increase in global coffee consumption over the years. This aligns with the earlier observation from the time series plot.

Seasonality: Given the decomposition was performed with a period of 1, seasonality is not applicable in this annual data. Seasonal decomposition typically requires data with more frequent observations (e.g., monthly or quarterly) to detect seasonal patterns.

Residuals: The residuals, which represent the noise or irregularities in the data after removing the trend and seasonality, do not show any systematic pattern, suggesting that the trend component captures most of the variability in the data.

This analysis confirms the long-term increase in global coffee consumption without any discernible seasonal patterns, likely due to the annual granularity of the data.

Observations¶

Robusta/Arabica: There's a clear upward trend for Robusta/Arabica consumption over the years. Arabica: Consumption of Arabica alone has increased albeit slightly over the years Robusta: The trend of consumption of Robusta alone is the lowest of all three. It fisplays a rather consistent pattern without noticeable increase.

Observations¶

The trend of the global average coffee consumption for each continent reveals the following:

South America: The continent has the highest upward trend over the years

Asia: Asian countries also have a noticeable upward trend over the years.

The remaining continents (Africa, Oceania & South America) display a rather consistend pattern with little to no increase yearly

Observations¶

The trend of the global average coffee consumption for the top 10 consumer countries:

  • There is a general upward trend in almost all the countries.
  • Venezuela experienced an upward trend from 1990 to 2008, which remained steady until 2016, but has since shifted to a downward trajectory.
  • Columbia initially experienced a downward trend from 1994 to 2007 but has increased noticeably ever since.
Observations¶
  • Most of the countries in the bottom 10 consumption group have alternating trends.

South America: The continent has the highest upward trend over the years

Asia: Asian countries also have a noticeable upward trend over the years.

The remaining continents (Africa, Oceania & South America) display a rather consistend pattern with little to no increase yearly

Conclusions¶

Insights¶

  • Arabica is the most consumed coffee type on average. It has been reported that Arabica generally tastes better than Robusta due to less caffeine than it's Robusta counterpart. In addition, approximately 75% of the world's coffee production is Arabica
  • Over the years, Brazil consumes the most coffee on average. This could be because Brazil is the most significant Arabica producer in the world.
  • There is a general increase in coffee consumption on average in the last 30 years.
  • South American countries consume the highest amount of coffee.
  • African countries consume the least amount of coffee on average.
  • The African country with the most coffee consumption is Ethiopia which could be attributed to an emerging urbanized middle class as detailed in this article
  • Of all countries in the top 10, only Venezuela has shown a downward trajectory in recent years. It has been reported that the countr is facing massive shortages of agricultural inputs including fungicides, herbicides, fertilizers, machinery and fuel.
